@NODE Tooltypes "Tooltypes"

@{B}                      - - --÷{· @{BG SHADOW}@{APEN 2}  MP3 TAG@{BG HIGHLIGHT}@{APEN 1}ger v1.3  @{BG BACKGROUND} ·}÷-- - -

                         @{B}  ·      @{U}USAGE - TOOLTYPES@{UU}       · @{UB}

  @{u}The Tooltypes@{uu}

  These are the tooltypes recognized by MP3Tagger v1.3:

     @{b}MP3DIR@{ub}       : The default directory where MP3Tagger's file requester
                    will start. For easier use, you should specify your
                    main MP3 drawer (if any) over here.

                    Default: @{b}MP3:@{ub}


     @{b}DETECTSPACES@{ub} : Switch the recognition and removal of the ending spaces
                    on. This prevents the string gadgets from getting filled with
                    spaces at the end (this is due to the internal TAG structure).
                    This should be enabled for everybody! Only put it off when
                    there is a problem reading the TAG Info correctly.

                    Note: The MP3 TAG structure is still saved according to the
                          official standard (blanks are filled with spaces).

                    Default: @{b}Off@{ub}


     @{b}USEMPEGA@{ub}     : Enable the use of the mpega.library by Stephane Tavenard.
                    This library is used to detect if the selected files are
                    really MPEG Audio files. You also need this library if
                    you want to display the MP3Info box. Please note that this
                    will slow down the loading of TAGs a bit (since the mpega
                    library has to check for the validity of the MPEG file).

                    Default : @{b}Off@{ub}


     @{b}MP3INFO@{ub}      : Display additional MP3 information such as the bitrate,
                    frequency and duration.

                    Default : @{b}Off@{ub}

@ENDNODE

******************************************************************************

@NODE CLIArguments "CLI Arguments"

@{B}                      - - --÷{· @{BG SHADOW}@{APEN 2}  MP3 TAG@{BG HIGHLIGHT}@{APEN 1}ger v1.3  @{BG BACKGROUND} ·}÷-- - -

                         @{B}  ·    @{U}USAGE - CLI ARGUMENTS@{UU}      · @{UB}

  @{u}The CLI arguments@{uu}

  The default template is as follows:

  F=FILENAME, DETECTSPACES/S, USEMPEGA/S, MP3INFO/S, NOGUI/S

  Here's a brief explanation of all the arguments:

     @{b}FILENAME@{ub}     : Should be obvious :) Type the filename @{b}with full path@{ub}
                    over here.


     @{b}DETECTSPACES@{ub} : Switch the recognition and removal of the ending spaces
                    on. This prevents the string gadgets from getting filled with
                    spaces at the end (this is due to the internal TAG structure).
                    This should be enabled for everybody! Only put it off when
                    there is a problem reading the TAG Info correctly.

                    Note: The MP3 TAG structure is still saved according to the
                          official standard (blanks are filled with spaces).

                    Default: @{b}Off@{ub}


     @{b}USEMPEGA@{ub}     : Enable the use of the mpega.library by Stephane Tavenard.
                    This library is used to detect if the selected files are
                    really MPEG Audio files. You also need this library if
                    you want to display the MP3Info box. Please note that this
                    will slow down the loading of TAGs a bit (since the mpega
                    library has to check for the validity of the MPEG file).

                    Default : @{b}Off@{ub}


     @{b}MP3INFO@{ub}      : Display additional MP3 information such as the bitrate,
                    frequency and duration.

                    Default : @{b}Off@{ub}


     @{b}NOGUI@{ub}        : Do not open the GUI interface but display the TAG in
                    the default CLI window instead.


@ENDNODE

******************************************************************************

@NODE GUIGadgets "GUI: The gadgets"

@{B}                      - - --÷{· @{BG SHADOW}@{APEN 2}  MP3 TAG@{BG HIGHLIGHT}@{APEN 1}ger v1.3  @{BG BACKGROUND} ·}÷-- - -

                         @{B}  ·       @{U}USAGE - GADGETS@{UU}        · @{UB}

 @{U}The Gadgets@{UU}

 (a) In the upper left corner is a small gadget with a little square in
     it. More advanced Amiga users call this the @{i}closegadget@{ui}.
     Click on this gadget (don't forget to move the mouse on TOP of it)
     to close the program down.

 (b) There are 5 (five) string-entry gadgets. Every single one of them
     will be written into the TAG data of the MP3 file. Just click on
     one of them to start entering the text. By default, pressing TAB
     in a string gadget will go to the next one, pressing SHIFT+TAB will
     go to the previous string gadget. Pressing RETURN (or ENTER) after
     entering data in a string gadget will also activate the next one.

     @{b}Title     :@{ub} Type the title of the MP3 song over here
     @{b}Performer :@{ub} The group's or artist's name should go here
     @{b}Album     :@{ub} If you happen to know what CD or Album it is on,
                 then type it over here.

     @{b}Comment   :@{ub} Anything you have to say about this particular
                 MP3file. Note: This is NOT the AmigaDOS comment, it is
                 a special field in the MP3 TAG structure.
     @{b}Year      :@{ub} The year of release.

 (c) There is one cycle gadget. You can select the music genre by pressing
     the mousebutton on top of it (or go back by pressing SHIFT + mouse).
     There are 141 available genre's, so get ready for some clicking ;).

 (d) To make everything more easy, a slider gadget was added to quickly
     scroll through all the available genres. You can also press the
     questionmark-button next to the slider gadget to invoke a listview
     gadget where you can also select the genre's.

 (e) There's a text display that says the current file you are operating
     with. To change the filename, just press the questionmark button
     next to the filename box.

 (f) You can use SAVE to save the current tag to the selected file, or
     you can use SAVE TO to write the tag to another MP3 file.

     Please note that you always have to select an MP3 file when saving
     to another file. MP3Tagger will NOT create a seperate TAG file, it
     will only write to the MP3 file you specify

     Also, when loading a TAG file, only the TAG structure gets read from
     the MP3 file, not the complete MP3 file itself!

@ENDNODE

******************************************************************************

@NODE GUIMenus "GUI: The Menus"

@{B}                      - - --÷{· @{BG SHADOW}@{APEN 2}  MP3 TAG@{BG HIGHLIGHT}@{APEN 1}ger v1.3  @{BG BACKGROUND} ·}÷-- - -

                         @{B}  ·    @{U}USAGE - MENU OPTIONS@{UU}      · @{UB}

 @{U}The Menu's@{UU}

 When you press the right mouse button you can choose between the following
 menu's and their options:

 (a) @{b}Project@{ub}
     @{b}--------@{ub}

     @{b}Load             :@{ub} Load the TAG structure from a MP3 file.
                        When no TAG structure can be found, the textfields
                        will be cleared.
     @{b}Save             :@{ub} Write the TAG to the current file.
                        (also see @{"Gadgets" LINK GUIGadgets})
     @{b}Save to...       :@{ub} Write the TAG to a file which you select.
                        (also see @{"Gadgets" LINK GUIGadgets})

     @{b}Erase tag...     :@{ub} Delete the TAG from the current file.

     @{b}About            :@{ub} Will popup a small information requester.
     @{b}Quit             :@{ub} Will stop the program.

 (b) @{b}Editor@{ub}
     @{b}-------@{ub}

     @{b}Clear all fields :@{ub} Clears all the string gadgets and resets the
                        genre selectors back to their defaults.

     @{b}Detect spaces    :@{ub} Toggle the detection and removal of the ending
                        spaces on and off. Also see the @{"Tooltypes" LINK Tooltypes} section.

     @{b}Use Mpega.library:@{ub} Toggle the usage of the mpega.library by Stephane
                        Tavenard on and off. Also see the @{"Tooltypes" LINK Tooltypes} section.

     @{b}Display MP3Info  :@{ub} Toggle the displaying of the MP3Info on and off.
                        Also see the @{"Tooltypes" LINK Tooltypes} section.


 (c) @{b}Preferences@{ub}
     @{b}------------@{ub}

     @{b}Load last saved  :@{ub} Load the last saved preferences from the MP3Tagger
                        icon. Also adjusts settings when you changed the icon.

     @{b}Save preferences :@{ub} Saves the current preferences to the MP3Tagger
                        icon. Will adjust the MP3DIR, USEMPEGA, DETECTSPACES and
                        MP3INFO values.

     @{b}Reset to default :@{ub} Will reset all preferences to default settings.

@ENDNODE

******************************************************************************

@NODE GUIKeys "GUI: Hotkeys"

@{B}                      - - --÷{· @{BG SHADOW}@{APEN 2}  MP3 TAG@{BG HIGHLIGHT}@{APEN 1}ger v1.3  @{BG BACKGROUND} ·}÷-- - -

                         @{B}  ·     @{U}USAGE - GUI HOTKEYS@{UU}      · @{UB}

  Pressing one of the following keys in the main window will invoke the
  following functions:

    @{b}l@{ub} or @{b}L@{ub} : Will load an MP3 TAG structure.
    @{b}s@{ub} or @{b}S@{ub} : Will save the MP3 TAG structure.
    @{b}a@{ub} or @{b}A@{ub} : Will save the MP3 TAG structure to another MP3 file.
    @{b}c@{ub} or @{b}C@{ub} : Will clear all string gadgets and reset genre gadget.
    @{b}ESC@{ub}    : Will quit MP3Tagger
    @{b}TAB@{ub}    : Will activate the first string gadget for text entry.
    @{b}?@{ub}      : Will popup the about requester.

@ENDNODE

******************************************************************************


@NODE FAQ "Known Problems and FAQ (Frequently Asked Questions)"

@{B}                      - - --÷{· @{BG SHADOW}@{APEN 2}  MP3 TAG@{BG HIGHLIGHT}@{APEN 1}ger v1.3  @{BG BACKGROUND} ·}÷-- - -

                         @{B}  ·   @{U}KNOWN PROBLEMS & FAQ@{UU}    · @{UB}

   The usage of MP3Tagger is quite easy, but if there should be any problems,
   then this list might come in handy.

                                  - - --÷-- - -

   @{B}Q : My screen is all black and I can't start MP3Tagger@{UB}
   A : Start the computer.

                                  - - --÷-- - -

   @{B}Q : When I start MP3Tagger, nothing happens. I don't see the GUI.@{UB}
   @{B}Q : MP3Tagger crashes!@{UB}
   A : Perform this checklist:
         * Do you have Kickstart 2.04 ?
           Check this by opening a CLI and typing: "version exec.library".
           If it says 37.xx or higher, then it's alright.

         * Do you have gadtools.library v36 ?
           Check this by typing "version gadtools.library" in the CLI.
           It should say 36.xx or higher.

         * Do you have the asl.library installed ?

         * Do you have at least 50kb of free memory in one block ?

       If this doesn't work, then please contact @{"the authors" LINK "Authors"}

                                  - - --÷-- - -

   @{B}Q : When I load a TAG, everything behind the texts is filled with spaces.@{UB}
   A : This used to be a problem in older versions of MP3Tagger. You can prevent this
       by turning on the 'DETECTSPACES' @{" tooltype " LINK Tooltypes} or @{" menu option " LINK "GUIMenus"}.
                                  - - --÷-- - -

   @{B}Q : I can only type in 30 characters in the string entry gadgets.@{UB}
   A : That is not a bug or an error. The maximum length of texts in the
       MP3 Tag structure is 30 bytes. (and 4 for the year).

                                  - - --÷-- - -

   @{B}Q : Sometimes MP3Tagger thinks a file is a MP3 Audio file while it's not!@{UB}
   A : This is not a problem of MP3Tagger, but of the mpega.library. It seems 
       to have some troubles in recognizing MP3Files. We have reported this to
       the author, Stephane Tavenard, and we guess it will be fixed in a later
       version of mpega.library. This problem seems to occur with LHA archives.

                                  - - --÷-- - -

   @{B}Q : There seems to be a problem with genres with value bigger than 84.@{UB}
   A : Aha, the famous PC @{i}We are so good that we can change all standards@{ui}-thingy.
       This problem only occurs when playing MP3 files that were modified by
       WinAMP. The authors of WinAMP (for Windows95/NT) have decide to change the
       standard, the default MP3 Genre list (as found on Unix machines) by inserting
       a new genre in the middle of the list.

       This is a step-by-step explanation of what happened (1):
        * All genre's are represented by one value in the MP3 tag structure.
          (A value from 0 to 255).
        * Every genre name has his own, unique number (for example,
          Opera has number 102).
        * When a new genrename is added, it simply gets a number which has not
          been used yet. (There currently are 115 genres in the UNIX source, so
          any new genre would get number 116, 117, and so on).
        * Now what happened on the PC: The authors of WinAMP decided to INSERT a
          new Genre in the list at position 84 (the new genre's name is Fast-Fusion).
          This means that all genre's with number 84 or higher shift DOWN one
          position. (For example, Opera, with genre number 102 would become genre
          number 103).
        * Basically, this means that ALL MP3 TAG readers (which do not following the
          standard set by WinAMP) will have problems with identifying genres with a
          number higher than 84.

       This is a rather annoying problem since WinAMP is the most used tool for
       playing MP3's and changing MP3 TAG structures. Furthermore, almost all new
       genre's that are added come from the WinAMP authors (currently 141 exist
       on the PC). We have decided to follow the WinAMP standard (actually we
       decided to do this since AmTAGID3 also uses the WinAMP lists).

                                  - - --÷-- - -

   @{B}Q : When are you going to use MUI for the user interface ?@{UB}
   A : We won't. It might be impossible to believe for some Amiga users,
       but there are actually people out there (including us) who don't
       like MUI at all (to be even more specific: we try to avoid it
       whereever possible). MUI is a very nice concept, but unfortunately
       slow and non-processor specific. Furthermore, there is no decent
       documentation available for assembler programmers, and we are NOT
       going to spend four months trying to figure out how to use all
       MUI features properly in assembler. And last but not least: MUI means
       leaving a portion of your program out of your hands. When coders
       use a MUI interface, there is absolutely no guarantee on how the
       output will be and how to properly interact with several things.
       Add a disinterest from the MUI programmer for processor specific
       versions & for assembler coders and you might understand why we
       do not use MUI.

       Besides, Gadtools (the standard Amiga Intuition enhancement to
       ease the programmer's life) has everything MUI's got to offer
       at an acceptable difficulty rate.

       If you really want a MUI interface, then we can only recommend
       you the excellent @{b}AmTAGID3 v1.6@{ub} by Georges Goncalves, which can
       also be found on Aminet (mus/misc/AmTAGID3.lha).


   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1) Thanks to Georges Goncalves for notifying the Amiga community of this
       problem in his AmTAGID3 v1.6 release.

@ENDNODE

******************************************************************************

@NODE Development "Programmer's Info"

@{B}                      - - --÷{· @{BG SHADOW}@{APEN 2}  MP3 TAG@{BG HIGHLIGHT}@{APEN 1}ger v1.3  @{BG BACKGROUND} ·}÷-- - -

                         @{B}  ·     @{U}PROGRAMMER'S INFO@{UU}     · @{UB}

   We realize that MP3 Information is not that common to find, so we decided
   to include the developper information we used:


   @{b}@{u}The MP3 TAG structure@{ub}@{uu}

   This structure can always be found at the END of an MP3 Audio file and has
   a size of 128 bytes. The TAG structure is defined this way:


   TAG                   - 3 bytes MP3 TAG identifier
   MP3 TITLE             - 30 bytes for the Title of this MP3
   MP3 PERFORMER         - 30 bytes for the Artist
   MP3 ALBUM             - 30 bytes for the Album this song is on
   MP3 YEAR              - 4 bytes to hold the year of release
   MP3 COMMENT           - 30 bytes for additional comment
   MP3 GENRE             - 1 byte describing the musical genre


   Or in assembler code:


   mp3tag:	dc.b	'TAG'                   ; MP3 TAG IDENTIFIER
   mp3title:	dcb.b	30,' '			; MP3 TITLE
   mp3perf:	dcb.b	30,' ' 			; MP3 PERFORMER
   mp3album:	dcb.b	30,' '			; MP3 ALBUM
   mp3year:	dcb.b	4,' '			; MP3 YEAR
   mp3comm:	dcb.b	30,' '			; MP3 COMMENT
   mp3genre:	dc.b	0                       ; MP3 GENRE


   As you can see, unused bytes are filled with SPACES and not with 0's.
   This is rather important (and rather annoying for coders ;) but the
   guys who invented this structure thought this is the best way.

   The Genre byte is pre-definied. You just write a hexadecimal value
   to this position and all MP3 TAG readers will use the following table
   to find out the genre:


    Genrenumber         Genrename

        000	        Blues
        001	        Classic Rock
        002	        Country
        003	        Dance
        004	        Disco
        005	        Funk
        006	        Grunge
        007     	Hip-Hop
	008		Jazz
	009		Metal
	010		New Age
	011		Oldies
	012		Other
	013		Pop
	014		R&B
	015		Rap
	016		Reggae
	017		Rock
	018		Techno
	019		Industrial
	020		Alternative
